A lot of theory was written about this kind of game. I don't know it as I should but it is normal to think about 6. Nxf7 first. If the king takes the knight Qf3+ recovers the piece. If you play something like Qf6 7. BxNd5 and I think it is worse for black. 
Black should think about something like 5. ... Na5. 
A very tactic position. I don't play it because if I want to I know I have to read a lot.
Probably better for white BxN leaving black's pawns doubled and isolated (with or without the queens).
Pure adrenalyne.
Same as before. I don't see what other advantage can white have from the position.
Or Qb3 to press on b7 and/or f7. If black answers Na5 Q+ and it is the same story - getting a doubled + isolated pawn.
Black has considered Bb4 for sure... would the queen chasing lead to somewhere? :-). Maybe just some developement.
Too late. White sees Qe4+ since after it the queen can take g7 or c7 but...
Smart but it kind of demostrates Bd7 was a waste of time.
Of course.
Losing a piece since white has a check. Better would have been the "quiet" Bb6. White would have had a nice attack here.
A piece is lost. Nevertheless black has some compensation and now it is his turn to attack.
Isn't white seeing Qxc2 threating Qxd2+?
Horrible being possible to play Bc3.
Hmmm... with the couple of white's inaccuracies the black position starts to be very interesting.
White realizes he cannot take the pawn: fxe3 Rxe3+ and white cannot take it back because of Rd1#.
Interesting is e2 22. Re1 Qd1 23. Bb2 but fails because now black cannot play Rxd2 due to Qxe7+...
And the piece is back with advantage...
Just a pawn and the position is open. Incredibly the storm vanished but black can be proud ;-)

I think that black must have tried to get the 2º row. 
In case he wants to throw its pawns c5... but it is not really relevant. Still...
Black must react to the c2 threat here... Maybe he thinks that it leads nowhere and just wants to simplify (the best way to win here).
So probably this move is a way of tempting him. But Qxc7+ then simply retreat is just a plain pawn loss.
And white loses his chances to recover the pawn.
...and now he loses another one. He can recover it but on the wrong side... black's pawns are equal to a rook in value...
It is difficult to see the followings. By now the game is even since the distance to promotion is the same for both pawns!
Can white support this pawn?
Can white support this pawn? Has he another choice?
Not with this move. With Kg2 Qa2+ would be answered with Qf2 and black... is lost I think! Funny isn't it?
Black must be careful with a perpetual trap. Qf1+ Kh2 a2 doesn't work because Qa3+...
A pity. It would have been a good lesson for black to go on until the win. Overall well played thoug.
i would continue with development if i was playing white with the simple 7.0-0 not 7.c5 as played next by white.
I want to keep my clergy's ( bishops ) eye on The h2 square.

I would of played more positional and tried for the center control of exchanges with the following
8.e4-dxe4 9.Nxe4 only best move 9...Nxe4 10.Bxe4-h6 11.0-0 0-0 12.Qc2-Nf6
If my opponent is not going to fight for the center then i will !!! nasty captain.
Rather white should of played 9.Nxe5 essential
Now the trouble starts for white.
Best under the circumstances

I was considering the following clear out but felt it left me no advantage and would give white a simplified position 10...exd4 11.Qc2-Ne5 12.Nxe5-Bxe5 13.Nxf6-Bxf6 14.0-0 h6 15.Rae1-Be6. remember these thoughts come from my mind at the time of play and not in post Motam of the game.
Perhaps 11...exd4 would of been better here for me but i wanted to get my knight into the action and head for the king but with reflection i think 11...exd4 more positional.
12.Bg5 pinning the knight would of been the move here.
The only correct way.
Perhaps to hang on longer 13.Qe2 instead of move played.
To late here now should of played this move earlier
I like this move by me straight to the point no fuss.
Never forgetting the rule never leave your king in the center or do so at your peril
A unfortunate blunder here by white a take back move feature would be good.
A gift given then i must oblige never know when you may get another.
17.g3 shouts out loud here.
time for a tactical shot here breaking the kings defences.
A doubble whammy tactical shotif the king takes with 19.kxh2 then 19...Bg4 drops whites queen.
allows white to hold on longer
Better than say retreating d7 or c8 the move played allows for the bishop to give a sermon to white when it later lands on c4 with a devastating blow.
allows sudden death well mate in a few.
Discoverd check nasty captain.
The squeeze begins
And the destroyer of souls

celebrating 4-20 with an inebriated opening choice. i'm going to improve on Swindler's variation in the Fred (1.e4 f5 2. exf5 e5?!) by investigating like totally peaceful developing moves before the e5 push is made. it came as a flash of inspiration while eating a bag of doritos with powdered donuts.
i paused here to decide which developing move to make and this gave white time to think. i believe this is what allowed 3. Qh5+. or maybe i'm just like you know.
white envisions taking the rook two different ways (4...hxg6 5. QxR) or (4...Nf6 attacking the queen with 5. g6 NxQ 6. g6xR=Q)
Bg7 isn't something expected at least not at this rating level so i prelude with a quick pause as if i've run through the variations and spotted something.
quick response needed

white has taken the bait and is taunted into making a quick mate. the mainline is 6. h7xN=Q+ KxQ 7. Bc4+ e6 when white's queen is under attack with undeveloped pieces. black is just starting his opening book while white must develop into an unfamiliar position having been taunted into thinking black is lost. such a taunted attacker in blitz most often loses as white in the mainline.
this threatens nf5 with mate on f7.
indirectly attacking the queen.
watch the queen charge in like a bull yet look at how well my pieces coordinate.
her safe squares are scarce.
the queen is trapped but she's seeing red.
guarding the knight to take the queen.
the bishop eyes g8 for mate.
ah!

white collapses in disgust. Fred's Swindle is a fun way to win blitz games for an average player. it's actually a fun way to lose as well because it trains the ability to defend losing positions with an exposed king which is helpful when you're a beginner like me since most of my games start out in losing positions with an exposed king especially when cartoons are on.
no good sq for the knight.

white who is rated about 1500 resigns as black's queen accentuates its lack of development. Fred's Swindle appears to need both timing and preparation. the taunting variations begin at move 5 or so and as white is largely undeveloped i think you could prep several moves ready to capitalize on white's errors as they need to spend more time in the unfamiliar opening to develop properly but they will also be charging in like a bull toward your exposed king. they will make more errors under such double duress and you will have a fun time beating them or sustaining their attacks for 50 moves before losing.
Black is preparing for E5 with E4 a possibility
Chase the bishop and create a space for my black squared bishop too
I am thinking of castling long and trying to smash my way through on the king side
g pawn is not as strong now
Am on the attack
Sacrifice time I think I can really cause some problems along that open file
Black needs to find an escape square for the king
Black is quite passive
There are a few traps here
Black has missed it
The bishop is going to fall
game over
One of my favorite openings. It's flexible and usually gives White the Q-side spatial advantage.
Logical.
I intend P-Q3 and a fianchetto of my KB giving me control of the light squares.
Very unusual and a little premature to develop the Q. It also blocks the Black KN from its natural square.
Now because of Black's Q and KN his KB is blocked in.
My King is now safe and I still have both center Pawns held in reserve to open the position at my leisure.
Strengthening the center and preparing to castle Q-side. With the K-side development so fouled up he has little choice.
I begin making preparations for a Q-side attack since Black will be forced to put his K on that side of the board.
First step: open a line for my QR to use.
Mission accomplished.

A mistake. This piece should have stayed on the Q-side to guard the King. 10...N-N1! was the proper move. This would also strengthen the QB3 square in preparation for ...P-QB3 sealing off the QB file as an avenue of attack.
The open QB-file is tempting but first I must secure my Pawns.
My Pawns are now secure and if Black tries 13...PxP e.p. 14 PxP preserves the intiative with a dicovered attack on the Black Q.
I finally seize the half-open QB file.
I'm not sure what exactly Black's idea is here. Two Pawns cannot by themselves conduct a successfuil attack. Although maybe the point is to gain space on the K-side.
I double on the QB file with the intent to weaken the Q-side Pawns... and an ancillary threat of mate which I didn't think he'd overlook.
He DID overlook it. Well then...
...let's go ahead and call it a day.
I am not used to this response.
I admire his urge To advance those pawns. It is a good move.
3. ...c5 stopped me from d4
I hate that pressure on b2.
I want your opinion. Was that a good trade for black?
That pawn is SO going down
I was making room for Ne6.
You should have seen prince's expression on his face after he touched that knight. I kinda felt sorry for the guy but I'm not goona let him take THAT back. 13. Ne6 would follow.
I felt kind of proud of myself at this point. I mean I didn't so much do an extrodinary move but I was beating a 900 for the second time in my life.
Well he certainly Isn't developing well.
I was not about to let him have any advantage. Now that I was ahead I wanted to keep him on the defensive mode.
My plan was to trade out queens.
He was trying to trap my rook in and I knew it. He did the exact next move I would have done.
I needed to retreat.
From this point we played on 13 more moves before he resigned. My rating in the tournament went from 665P16 to 709P21
Sicilian
Much better is the following: 29. Rd7  e3  30. fxe3 fxe3  31. Qe2 Qf2+  32. Qxf2 exf2+
Better would be: … Rxd6 30.  Qxd6  Qxd6  31. Rxd6 fxe3
31. Qxe3  Rxe3  32. Rxf6 Re2  33. Rb6 Re8e7  34. a4 Rc2 should be considered.
Best moves: … Qb5 35.  Kg2  h6
Best: 36. Kg1  Qc5  37. Qxe3 Qf5  38. Rd1 a5  39. Qd4 Rf7
… Qe4 36.  Qxe3  Qh1+  37. Kd2 Qxh2+
Much better is: 37. Qxe3  Qb1+  38. Rd1 Qf5
The game is lost at this point for white... the following would keep the game going for some time: 38. Kd2  Qxb2+  39. Kd1 Qb3+  40. Kc1 a5  41. c4 Rf1+  42. Qxf1 Qxe3+
Vienna Game.
Black steps out of opening book targeting the week f7 square.
Point being Nc6 4. Nxe5 Nxe5 5. d4.
Black solidifies his position with his bad bishop outside of his pawn structure.
d3 seemed week due to blacks bishop.  d4 may not be possible later so I challenge the center right away.
Bg5 was considered.
locking the bishop in for the time.  Nxd5 is met with caution.  8. Nxd5 c6!?
!? white can't take on dxc6 Qxd4 losing a knight.
I almost considered not playing this move.  But it does break up black structure which is a key to my attack later on.
Na4!? Qb4 Nxc5
Now the queen has a choice Qxc4 Ne4 or Qxc5 Bb3.  I believe the correct move though it fuels a bit of an attack for white is Qxc4.
keeping the bishop under lock and key.
Connecting the rooks and allowing a possible check Qg3.
Prevents Rd1.
unpins the knight.
Trade of knights Giving the bishop little to no life but its still a good bishop and the endgame should we reach it could be quite good for white.
Critical point what can black do? a5 is met by a4 Bg4 is met by Qf4.
Black makes a choice though not a good one.  White will have full control of the e-file.
Give the bishop chase.

Black had no where to go so decides to sac the bishop for structure.  Though I have a very good attack going in which mate is soon. Best was probably Bg6.  I believe it is force mate from here stop and see if you can find it.
only move is Kg8
Forcing Kh8
f6! this is the critical move for the forced mate.

Black is done Rxe8 Qg7#. Black cannot loosen the king good enough to do continuous-checking Bxg2+ Kxg2 and blacks out of Checks after Q+ KxQ.  Black can't do anything that doesn't protect g7 due to Qg7# what a beautiful pinning mate that would be.  Blacks last option doesn't change anything Qf8 Rxf8 and its back to the same position just with the rook on f8 and no black queen.
The Center Counter defense and if white is not greedy and developes normally he should maintain an advantage.
Now the problems for white seem to be starting. Better is Bb4+ and prepare to castle king-side.
A player of this rating should reject any plan that makes his pawn structure look like this.
Not good. Black can exchange this bishop off and have three developed pieces against one and have a better pawn structure but still a pawn down.
There is a lot of undefended room behind white's pieces.
Weakening his position even further.
Clearly the losing move brought about by the undended squares deep in the white position.
Qe3+! Resignable now because of the material loss that can't be avoided.
Nf4? loses on the spot. Nothing but undefended pieces scattered about.
This defense held because of poor play by white and can't be considered the best response to e4.
Having lost the right to castle and a pawn White must now develop quickly or lose the game.
White must attack the pawn chain and threatens Bzf7.
? Which Black overlooks.
Black wants to play Ba6+.
White blocks that and begins a plan to harass the Black Queen.
Now Black has to be careful.
? This move subjects Black to a withering attack.
Nxg5! White a pawn and seizes the initiative.
Black faces a similar attack after Qe8.
Bh5! Drives the Q away and tightens the net around the B king.
Qf6 would lose the Q to Nd5+.
Nd5+ Going for the Kill. If instead e5?  Black had ...Nxe5 in response
! A good try.
Ke1! Necessary to avoid the troublesome...Bxd5+
Basically forced.
Nf7! Black was hoping to get some freedom for the piece but White wants to take with the N on e5.
Nearly forced if Black wants to retain hope of surviving in the complications.
Qf3+! White has the mating net set up.
Hopes the mate threat will slow White down. But White has a forced mate from this position. Can you see it?
Having manuevered the Q to support the N this check is fatal.
Black never gets the chance to mate on e2.
?! Not sure why White thought this was good it opens up lines of attack on the Q side.
Black wastes no time in beginning the attack.
Intending to provoke c3
To force f4 to take the pressure off of e5 so that Black can concentrate on attacking the W king.
To provoke more weaknesses.
Black wants the N to go to c5.
hoping for a pawn exchange to open lines.
Locks in the K side.
! Fairly obvious but White has good moves now.
? Overlooks checkmate. There are not any good moves but White could fight on with Rd2.
? Quick move forgot about the immediate checkmate although Black has an easy win anyway after say Kb1.
Its over
Book opening so far.
The amateur plays a sharp variation.
Reshevsky is unworried and simply continues developing.
Trying to break the center apart.
Now capturing the White QN will not double White's Pawns.
Development proceeds apace.
Putting the question.
Freezing the Bishop in place but also playing for a trap: PxB?? would now be answerd by ...QxR!
Adding support and breaking the pin.
Leaving the Bishop en prise.
Reshevsky pounces winng the Bishop and attacking the Queen.
Indirectly guarding the Queen by means of a trap...
...which Reshevsky falls straight into. Now the lightning bolt strikes.
Game set and match!
So far all book play.
White's advantage in development is counterbalanced by my stronger center Pawns.
The first tactical skirmish leaves neither side with any advantage gained.
To prevent the Knight from planting itself at QN5.
Now I have a small material advantage though not enough to win yet.
I've been looking for a chance to castle and finally do. Now the middle-game begins.
Right now my center Pawns give me a space advantage. I need to either maintain this or convert it into material.
I contemplate a general advance on the Q-side.
Now I'm ahead by two Pawns which should be a big enough margin to win. Time to think about trading down and simplifying the game.
One pair of minor pieces zapped...
Offering a Queen trade.
Now I have a powerful passed Q pawn and with the Queens gone the endgame has been reached.
Back to 1 Pawn ahead but it's 3 moves from Queening. I like my chances.
White has to blockade the Pawn.
Now I plan to use the Pawn as a battering ram.
White prevents this. But White is on the defensive. I'm free to do as I wish.
I aim for the unprotected Bishop.
If the Bishop isn't guarded and doesn't move I can capture it. I can now also remove the White Knight blockading my Pawn.
Wow best of both worlds thanks to this blunder. Now I pick up the B and my Pawn is free to advance.
Gaining time by attacking the Rook.
Now the Bishop and Pawn protect each other freeing my Rooks for other duties. I also unmask an attack on the White QR.
If Black wants to give me the Rook I'll gladly take it.
Now the Knight is en prise and falls.
Just a matter now of when White gives up.
To avoid any possibility of a swindle and a back-rank mate.
It's all over but the shouting.
White voluntarily gives up his last piece and now has no chance of even pulling a last-ditch swindle.
With my KRP headed on an unstoppable journey towards becoming a Queen White finally gives in.

When this game stated we both were rather close in our ratings differential.  A few years later the difference was much larger.  Lesson?  Do not put a bunch of faith in ratings.  Just try to play your best.

2...d5 might put us in a Veresov Opening which is not a huge problem for Black.  It is one of the BPWUW openings (best player will usually win).  Not a lot of theoretical advantage to be gained for either side if I play 2...d5.  An opening that is NOT a BPWUW is the Rauzer Attack.  A well versed weaker player can take out a much higher rated opponent with either color.  Any of those long theoretical openings can yield positive results for the better prepared.  The Veresov might be that way but I tend to think not...

We are probably in a Nimzovitch Defense now: 1.e4 Nc6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 would be one move order besides the game's move order.  I am not a regular player of that line with either color.  I do have some books on the opening and a few more that cover some of the main lines.  Hugh Myers has the best book but to use the contents requires study and analysis to find the best lines.
I'm not sure if this is better than 3...d6 or 3...e5.
White has the dark squares under control and Black has the light squares somewhat under control.
An option is 11..f6 when Black seeks to attack the pawn chain.  Ultimately the pawn chain survives but lines are opened.  Most likely the f and/or d files.

The Kings are safe most pieces are developed and the pawn chains are locked to a degree.  White has not taken the opportunity to ruin Black's Queen side pawns but that just means the Bishop is valued more than doubled pawns.  I might have tried 12.Bc4 as an alternative to 12.f4 or 12.Bxc6.  Not playing 12.f4 allows White to attack the pawn chain with f2-f3 later.
A mainly defensive move to save the Queen side pawn formation's integrity. There was not a lot of offensive potential for the Bishop on g6 either.  So maybe later it becomes an offensive move too?
Ah yes...13.b4 gives me a target to work on immediately and that is not a bad thing.
Maybe I can activate a Rook in the process.

The first skirmish is over.  Black did better.  White retreated to a passive post and Black has a tempo to move (...b7-b6) as a result.  Position is about even.  Neither backward pawn is under pressure.
White has voluntarily made both my Bishops good.  White is also controlling the center and the squares adjacent to the center. Black has a piece of the center too.
Defensive again... in case of d4-d5 soon.  Black has three pieces contesting the square and White has only two attacking at present so some preparation is needed for the d4-d5 thrust.
The Knight's scope was increased after 17.a4 but I am worried about c4-c5.
I failed to note that even though I had d5 covered I did not have f5 under control if ...exd5 is played.
More defense...fixing the previously noted defensive issue asap!
White's pawns are definitely weaker now than they were a few moves back.
Third skirmish looks to favor Black after 20...Bc5.
Capture with tempo.
Three threats to a4 versus two defenders.  There are five potential attackers.
White opts to ignore the threat meaning lose the pawn and trade some pieces but takes immediate control of the open d-file.
I do not agree with giving up the exchange with the a-pawn however.  You need to GAIN material (pawns) or get a definite positional plus for an exchange down trade.
What file is better to control?
Attacking the backward pawn but no other pieces can quickly apply pressure.
White probably needs to keep g2 under control now.
The pawn moved but the square is still vital.
This seems premature in retrospect.  Maybe 31...Nd3 with plans to go to e1 is a beter idea.
32.Bf3 Rxd2+ 33.Qxd2 exd2 looks to be okay for Black but no more.
This has more impact with the White Knight on f3 instead of the Bishop.
Not the right choice unfortunately....game over. Maybe 33.Rxb7 is really no better.
And again a few years later our ratings were vastly different.  However our play was not vastly different in this game.
The game starts with the Gruenfeld Defence and my opponent chose a very sharp line that gave me quite a few headaches as the game ensued.

The Classical main line and one of the first historic attempts to refute the Gruenfeld. It's still seen with regular frequency in modern practice. White's idea is to place each piece on a very active and secure post while trying to maintain the central pawn duo as it is.
The standard plan for Black is to create pressure against the White centre especially the d-pawn.

White's main idea behind this setup. He doesn't want to push either on of his central pawns and break the phalanx formation otherwise Black's pieces will just use the central squares as outposts and play around White's pawns.
Black's tactical idea is to use the loose position of the Bc4 to rearrange his pieces so as to hold the centre.
12. Bxf7+ is still very much played and can be quite dangerous.
The point in delaying this move is very simple. Black wants to keep the c-file closed as White won't be able to reply to 11...Na5 with 12. Rc1

A very thematic position for the Gruenfeld but one that has slowly subsided from practice because of new discoveries in the Bronstein gambit which starts with 14. d5. I'm not that concerned about it and I'm actually looking forward to playing against it provided an opponents accommodates me of course.
An old idea White sacrifices a pawn to hold the centre. The idea is to vacate the Rook from a1 so that White can play d5 and gain space.
No need to be compliant taking the pawn is relatively safe.

The old variation starting with 15. d5 Bb3 16. Qd2 e6 17. Qb4 exd5 18. Rc5 Bc4 19. Rxa5 Bxd3 20. Rxd5 Bxe2 21. Rxd8 Rfxd8 has fallen out of favour since Black is the only one with real winning chances. This move tries to exploit the two Black pieces that are on the edge of the board. White definitely has pressure for the sacrificed pawn.
15...Be6 is way too cooperative. This is the best way to fight for the initiative.
White still keeps the Queen on the Q-side to pressurize Black's position.
A bad positional move since now there are weak squares on the Q-side for White to invade but there is no other decent way to untangle the Black pieces.

A relatively new try and not a bad one at that. White's idea is to double Rooks and dominate the c-file. Note that because of weak white squares on the Q-side Ba6 is possible in some lines thus Black is forced to accept White's domination on the c-file.
Forced since White was threatening to exchange a Rook for two pieces.
White managed to double with tempo and already has ideas of infiltrating Black's 7th rank.

The theoretical recommendation and it served me pretty well in this game. Trying to simplify the position with 18...Rc8 19. Nf4 Qd6 20. Qxd6 exd6 21. Nxe6 Rxc3 22. Rxc3 fxe6 23. Bb5 leaves White with enough compensation for the pawn thanks to his Bishop pair and Black's weak pawn structure and bad Knight on a5.
Avoiding the exchanges with good motive. After the Queen swap Black can contest the c-file and reduce White's compensation to zero.
No time to wait and the more pieces are exchanged the more the extra pawn will be felt.
White exchanges my white square defender but it's all in order.
Not accepting the exchange allows Rc7 and Black will slowly suffocate.
This move gives me enough time to secure the 7th rank.
An ungainly move but necessary. If White is given time to play Rc7 d5 and Nd4 Black has no counterplay.
An interesting try and directed against my last move. White wants to reduce the scope of play of my pieces to the absolute minimum.
I in turn use White's move to force the exchange of Queens and a pair of Rooks.
25. d5 transposes after 25...b5. White must keep his remaining Rook active on the c-file before I play Nc4 and gain the upper-hand.

Perhaps 26. Rc8 was slightly more accurate but this needs to be played eventually. White wants to use the extra space to get his pieces on ideal spots and generate more than enough initiative to recover the pawn.
With the idea of Nc4.
Absolutely forced. Now the Rook can attack the Q-side pawns from behind while at the same time keeping the Bf8 under lock and key.
Directed against White's matting net starting with Bh6. Now I could reply with Rd8 and force the exchange of Rooks. I also use the opportunity to get the Knight into play.
A nice and obvious move. White activates his pieces by using his space advantage.
The best move. The White Rook was far too active on the last rank.
Keeping the Rook active is an imperative. Now the Knight is attacked and I must decide what to do about it.
This looks like a step back and maybe it is. 29...Nd6 was worth considering but I was in a greedy mood.
30. Nc6 is a basic draw after 30...Nxc6 31. dxc6 e5 32. Ra7 b4 33. Rxa6 b3 34. Rb6 Rc8 35. Kf1 b2 36. Rxb2 Rxc6. My opponent was trying to win this.

As was I. The Knight finally arrived to c4 and I can breath a sigh of relief because I have a much better chance to hold on to the extra pawn now even if that means suffering for a short time. OK maybe not a short amount of time but a pawn is a pawn and it beats suffering for nothing.

White keeps playing aggressively and forcing me shut my own bishop in. The alternatives weren't much to look at however. After 31. Kf2 Rd6 32. Nc6 a6 33. Ra8 Nxe3 34. Kxe3 exd5 35. exd5 a5 36. Rb8 a4 Black has better long term prospects provided he doesn't allow any exchange of pawns which isn't an easy task by any measure.

A double-edge move because it restricts the Bf8 further and it also weakens e-pawn and the white squares on the K-side. The main advantage of it is that is forces the White Bishop to relinquish its very active post.

Probably the best place to retreat. Now the Nc4 is kept under control and I'm not allowed to develop my Bishop on the c1-h6 diagonal. After the alternative 32. Bh4 I could have played 32...b5! (giving back the pawn to activate the pieces) 33. Nxb5 Rb8 34. Nd4 Bh6! and I have a good position all of a sudden.
The a-pawn was under attack and pushing it was the only way to defended it.

A very good place to keep the Rook. White was smart to avoid restoring material balance with 33. Nxb5 because after 33...e6! the Ra7 is poorly placed and White must move to King in order to avoid an embarrassing double attack. Now I can't protect the b-pawn by advancing it because that leaves the Knight en-prise.
Retreating the Knight from the now insecure c4 square and preparing the b4 advance in case White doesn't take on b5 at once.

An excellent move. My opponent is avoiding all the pitfalls with great skill. The King is brought close to the centre to avoid any back rank tricks and also traps on the dark squares. But why was the very natural looking 34. Nxb5 worse than this move? The reason is that after 34...e6 White can be lured into what seems like a dangerous attack starting with 35. Nd4 exd5 36. Ne6 Bd6 37. Rg7+ Kh8 38. Bh6 Re8 39. exd5 Re7 and the attack has stalled and the a-pawn is looking like it might just queen.
The intended and best move. The pawns are pretty advanced now but they are not yet very dangerous because White with his previous move has brought an excellent piece to supervise them his King.
Now the pawns don't seem so menacing and White can use his active pieces to either capture them or direct his threats elsewhere.

A very ugly move but I was under the impression that f4 followed by Nc6 is very powerful. The problem is that after this move it will take extraordinary means to activate the lousy Bf8. A much better try was 35...Ra8 and after 36. f4 Nf7 37. Nc6 b3 White can choose between 38. Nxe7 Bxe7 39. Rxe7 a4 40. Ba3 Rb8 41. Bb2 a3 42. Bxa3 b2 43. Bxb2 Rxb2+ 44. Kf3 Rd2 with a very promising endgame and 38. e5 (a much better try) a4 39. Ba3 fxe5 40. fxe5 e6 41. d6 Nd8 42. Nxd8 Rxd8 43. Kd3 Rb8 with a complicated ending.
Keeping the pressure on my pawns. The only drawback is that it allows me to activate my Rook.
What to do with the Bishop now?
An active looking move but perhaps 37. Kd1 was slightly better.
Now I can defend my pawns with tempo.
Pretty forced. The active looking 38. Nc6 fails to 38...e5 39. Bf2 b3 40. Kd3 Nb2 41. Kc3 Nd1+ 42. Kxb3 Nxf2 43. Rxa5 and I'm sure I could have won this.
The point to this move is to prevent White from achieving a favourable pawn structure on the K-side starting with g4.
Inviting me to play 39...h4 and fix the pawn structure on the K-side but after which my Bf8 would effectively be locked in an iron cage. I had something else in mind.
A pawn sacrifice meant to activate my awful Bishop. Perhaps 39...h4 wasn't that bad but I had had enough of playing with only two pieces.

Taking with the Knight leads to an almost forced variation after 40. Nxf5 b3 41. Bd4 a4 42. Rxa4 b2 43. Bxb2 Nxb2 44. Ra2 Rc2+ 45. Kf1 Rd2 46. Ra7 Nc4 47. Nxe7+ Bxe7 48. Rxe7 which is again a very complicated ending that both sides can try to win.
Over-protecting a5 and getting rid of the White's annoying d-pawn.
Fixing the pawn structure and threatening Ra8 which wasn't very good right now because of 42...Rxf5 43. Kd3 Nb2+ with an immediate draw. White is still bent on winning this. I love fighting chess.
I exchanged pawns on my weaker flank to lower White's prospects.

An odd looking place for the Bishop but the g-pawn must not fall. I'm trying to win this too and the more natural looking 43...Ng7 would have almost forced White to draw with 44. Ra8+ Kh7 45. Nxg5+ Kh6 46. Nf7+ and so on.
The drawback is that White can activate his Bishop.
Passed pawns must be pushed. I must act quick and generate enough threats before White weaves a matting net around my King.

The forceful 45. h4 trying to squeeze the mate in fails after 45...Rxd4! (eliminating White's best piece which was both attacking and defending at the same time) 46. Nxd4 b2 47. Rb7 gxh4 and there are too many runaway pawns for White to catch. The move played gives White time to bring the King closer to the connected pawns on the Q-side.
The Knight is threatened. Where do you think it should go?

A good place where Knight is safe and is eyeing the queening square of the b-pawn. 46...Ne5+ forces White to draw after 47. Ke4 Rxd4+ 48. Kd4 b2 and White must draw with the Knight checks because Rb8 fails to Nc6+. It's very interesting that the Black King cannot come to d7 because after Rd8+ he's forced to take the forking c6 square and that gives White enough time to win the b-pawn and the game. 46...Nd6 fails to 47. Rh8 and White has enough time to capture the Bh6 and stop the pawns from advancing too far.
Put your Rook behind the most advanced pawn. That isn't an empty statement and it's the best way to play against connected pawns with a Rook.
What else?
The King comes into the fray.
The Rook must stay on the d-file. Trying to play 48...Rb5 is thwarted by 49. Rh8! and mate is looming.

The last try for a win. Trying to play slowly with something like 49. Bb2 can only lead to a disaster after 49...Nc4 50. Rh8 Nxb2 51. Rxh6 Rd6! 52. Nxg5+ Ke8 53. Ne6 Kd7 (53...Rxe6 only leads to a draw after 54. dxe6 Kf8 55. Rh8+ Kg7 56. Ra8 a3 57. Rxa3 Nc4 58. Ra8 b2 59. Rb8 b1Q 60. Rxb1 Nd2+ 61. Kf5 Nxb1 62. g5 Nc3 63. h4 Nb5 64. h5 and White holds his ground) 54. Rh8 Rxe6! (now this works) 55. fxe6+ Kxe6 56. Rh6+ Kf7 57. Rh7+ Kg6 58. Rxe7 a3 and the Black pawns triumph.

The only move. This was the main reason why the Rook had to stay on the d-file. 49...gxh4 loses to 50. Bh8! followed by g5 and White's attack is very strong even with the reduced material on the board.

Taking with the Knight is worse because after 50...gxh4 51. Nxb3 h3! 52. Kf3 Nc2 53. g5! (worse is 53. Nc5 Ne1+ 54. Kg3 h2 55. Kxh2 Be5+ 56. Kh3 Bxb8 57. Nxa4 and it's a simple matter of technique to win this) Bxg5 54. Nc5 a3 ( 54...h2 is met by 55. Rh8 the point behind 53. g5! the h-file is cleared with tempo) 55. Ra8 and the only one in danger of losing this is White.
Another passed pawn is born.
If that pawn ever gets to g6 with tempo the Black King is doomed.

Try to play tricky intermediate moves like 51...Nc2+ is not recommended. After 52. Ke4 Bg7 53. g6+ (remember what I said a move earlier?) Kf6 54. Nxg7 Kxg7 55. Re8! and White will deliver a Queen first despite all the passed Black pawns.

The King has to come forward or else my King can escape and the pawns will win. For example after 52. Kd3 h3  53. Nd8+ Ke8 54. Ne6+ Kd7 55. Rd8+ Kc6 56. f6 ( trying to close the diagonal and catch the Q-side pawns with the King) exf6 57. Kc3 fxg5+! 58. Nxg7 Nb5+ 59. Kb2 Nd6 and there are too many pawns for White to keep tabs on all of them.

A slight inaccuracy that leaves me a bit worse but not without hope. 52...Nc2 was the better move making room for the pawns to march in tandem. An interesting try is 53. g6+ Kf6 54. Nxg7 Kxg7 55. Re8! b2 56. Rxe7+ Kf6 (56...Kf8 loses outright to 57. f6 with mate to follow) 57. Rf7+ Ke5 58. Rb2 Nd4 59. Rxb2 Nxf5 60. Rf2 a3 61. Kb4 a2 61. Rxa2 Kf6 62. Ra6+ Kg7 63. Kc5 h3 and the pawnless ending is a dead draw. A very dangerous attempt is 53. Nd8+ Kg8 54. g6 Be5 55. Ra8 Kg7 56. Ne6+ Kh6 57. Rxa4 Kh5 58. g7 Bxg7 59. Nxg7+ Kg5 60. Ne6+ Kxf5 61. Nd4 Nxd4 62. Rxd4 with a draw also. The Rook can hold the pawns but it's not enough to capture them all.
The only move. Ke8 doesn't work now because there is no escape through d7 anymore.
Repeating the position not a problem in CC but in OTB it can have a psychological effect on your opponent who might just crack under pressure and deviate with a worse move.
Threatening mate with Ne6.

The only move. It prevents a very nasty discovered check it forces the Rook of the b-file or the 8th rank it makes room for the King to escape and it prepares to advance the h-pawn. Talk about doing multiple things at once. I'd just like to add a small opinion of mine. When there are advanced passed pawns on both flanks or more generally there is heavy play on both flanks a Bishop comes very close to the value of a Rook because it can focus fire defend blockade on both sides of the board and sometimes all of that at once.

The only move for White as well. Playing 57. Rc8 suddenly loses after 57...Kg7 58. Ne6+ Kh6 59. Kd5 (forcing the Bishop from its over-active post in the middle of the board) Bb2! (guarding against Rc1) 60. g7 (otherwise White has to sit and what the h-pawn queening) Bxg7 61. Rc1 b2! ( advancing with tempo) 62. Rh1 Kh5 (White was threatening mate) 63. Rxh3+ Kg4 and Black will soon have a full fledge Queen on his hands.
Forced or else mate follows.
Again the only move. Trying to change the move order loses because after 58. Rxa4 h2 59. Ne6+ and Black can play Kf6 because there is no mate on f8 anymore.
Again the only move as mentioned earlier Kf6 gets the King mated with Rf8.

After an incredible long struggle White finally gets to capture at least one of the troublesome passed pawns. Again this is the only move that keeps White in the game. Trying to play something like 59. Kd5 gets clobbered by 59...Nc4 and the Black Bishop is the star of the show.
Again the only move. Mate was threatened on h4. This Bishop is sure making up for the lost time in the earlier part of the game when it was the worst piece on the board.
Not forced anymore but the best try. White wants to make a Queen for himself as well.
60...Bxg7?? 61. Rh4#. The King is the only piece that can catch the pawn.
White is still determined to queen that pawn.
The shortest way to splitting the point after an arduous battle. The awesome Bishop sacrifices itself for White's most dangerous pawn.
Taking with the Knight loses to 62...b2. White must still be careful.
But so must I. After 62...Kh6 63. Rg3 the threat of mate gives White just enough time to capture all the pawns and use his last remaning soldier to bring home the point.
The game is almost drawn now. White munches one more for the road.

There won't be enough mating material left on the board after 66...b1Q 67. Rxb1 Nxb1 68. Nxh3 Kf6 so draw was agreed at this point. A very difficult and sharp endgame that was like walking a tightrope that is set aflame behind you.

I consider this one of my best games not because it contains any brilliant sacrifices but rather because of the subtle moves that lead to an end-game plus despite good play from my opponent. 
I of course started with my favourite king's pawn!
The Sicilian is my friend's standard reply to 1.e4 so I had prepared accordingly...
I opt for the closed Sicilian in order to steer the game into unfamiliar lines.
Don't want a black knight on d4 just yet!
The knight wants to provoke 9. ..e5 so he can occupy d5 - while at the same time threatening to go to h5 and trade off knights to bring the queen to h5.
Success! The knight is stabled.
One horse is as good as another...

The pawn break which I had planned for a while in anticipation of Bxd5 - the idea (as will become clear) is to create an ugly passed pawn on d5 that black will have to blockade as well as opening the f-file for my rooks.
the knight must move...
Not 14. Bxd4 because that gives black an advance pawn wedge and I want my bishop to keep ministering for a while yet!
Begone foul beast!
The Queen is hoping to dethrone the black king with various moves including Bxh6 and Be4.

My opponent wisely protects f7 but leaves a convenient sally port on g6. 
I analysed the bishop sac on h6 here but decided her Royal Highness needed some more manoeuvrings first.
Crude (and unlady-like) but the threat Bxh6 is now very real. The moves Be4 and Qh7+ are also looming which will storm the castle and give mate.
Cat fight! The only way to relieve the pressure is to let the wives have a scrap
I have the bishop pair now I have to prove their worth. Ideas based on the long g1-h7 and hi-b7 diagonals begin marinading.
The knight blockades well yet is hampered by the pawn on d3 from leaping into my camp and causing mayhem - who says doubled pawns are bad?!
My gun-sights are fixed on a7. I plan 22. a5 and if 22...b6xa5 then Bxc5 and Rxa5. 22...b5 falls to bxc5 as well.
Hoping to harass the white bishop and start a pawn storm on the king-side.
Black defends but weakens his back rank as we shall see.

A protecting move (to take the burden off d3) and a waiting move. I wait for the black rook to move to f6 further weakening the back rank and allowing the bishop to retreat to a happier hunting ground on the h1-h7 diagonal.
Here comes the pawn storm! However the wind is taken out of the juggernaut's sails completely by white's next move.

I allow myself a !! here. The weakness of black's back rank is his undoing. 25...c5xb4? 26.a5xb6 and the pawn cannot be taken by either the pawn on a7 nor the d8 bishop due to the pin on the rook at a8!
25...b6xa5 26.b4xc5 and a deadly centralised pawn mass emerges that black cannot stop.
Blacks only hope is to try and counter attack on the king-side.
The evil bishop stays on his powerful diagonal.
The pressure against the a8 square is ready to blow.
Better than 29. d4xe4 because then the black knight enters white's position with 29...Rg5+ and Nxc4.
The beginning of a desperate attempt to relieve the pressure from the f2 bishop.
The poor rook at a8 isn't having a good day!

The position is hopeless for black as the white pawns will grind up the board relentlessly. e.g. 33...c5xb4 34.Rxa7 Rb8 35.c5 Nc8 36.Rc7. Black cannot retreat his rook to help on the back rank because his king is in the way!

A very common variation of the Nimzo-Indian defense. The most popular line here involves White playing for the two bishops with 5.a3 Bxc3+ 6.Qxc3 keeping the pawn structure intact where Black normally prefers 6...b6 to develop the queenside bishop to the long diagonal. I normally prefer the gambit line 6...b5!? 7.cxb5 c6 with lightsquare play for the pawn.

Normally Black plays 5...b6 after e3 here with the idea that White has failed to take control of central light squares so Black should try to take advantage of this. Of course my theoretical knowledge is deficient given that I only recently started studying the Nimzo-Indian. 5...d5 also leads to a common position although the normal move order there is 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Bb4 4.Qc2 d5 5.e3 O-O. Since I don't play 4...d5 of course I wouldn't play 5...d5 here.
A fairly standard maneuver...Black wants to occupy the central light squares with his knight and pawns so Ne4 allows d5 and f5.
8...f5 is probably more accurate. If White takes the c5 pawn there Black does best to play a5 preventing b4 before playing to recover the pawn.
Actually not what I had in mind... 9...a5 is clearly a better move.

Black's plan of blocking the center like this is not terribly convincing. White could try to take advantage of this with the immediate 13.cxd5 after which 13...exd5 leaves too many holes and 13...Qxd5 14.Bc4 should be advantageous for White.
Of course this is okay too.
A dubious move...much better was 17...Nd6 where White has only a slight advantage.
Necessary. Otherwise after 19...Bb7 White wins the e6 pawn with 20.Qb3.
21.e5! is a very strong move leading to a forced clear advantage for White. However 21.Bc4 is also very strong it's unclear which move is better.
The only defense... if 23...g6 White wins with 24.Bxg6!.
Perhaps stronger is 24.Rxf8+ Kxf8 25.Qxh7 with a clear advantage to White who plans 26.Nxe6+ and 27.Bf5 winning back the Exchange.
Preventing Qg3 and eyeing the d2 square.
Practically forcing Rxf4 which is actually good for White anyway. But I don't see anything better. Of course 27.Qg3 is also possible with advantage to White.
After this error White should only have a draw. 29.Bf1 Qxb2 30.Qe3 was indicated where White can keep his advantage.

The losing move. After this move Black's mate threats become unbearably strong. 34.Qf4 was completely forced after which Black can try something like 34...Bf3!? (gxf3 loses to Qf2+ and Qxf1 mate Qxf3 loses to Qd4+ followed by Nf2+) or a more subtle move like Qxa3 with equal chances.
This forces White to give up his queen to avoid mate but it's hard to find a recommendation for White here.
Black goes with 1...f5.  Not what I usually see.  Often I see 1...d4 which leads into a Queen's Gambit game.
Given that this looks nothing like a QG game now I decide to go with a game I'm comfortable with--a fianchetto of my LSB.
5.d4  I decide to stake a direct claim to the center.
Taking more of the center.
I'm not sure what type of opening White has (aside from Reti).  fritz has told me that Black has engaged in a Dutch Stonewall defense.
The first foray by either player into the other's territory.

Black now has quite the pawn chain extending.  GameKnot scores this as -0.22 advantage Black.  Fritz says the game is equal.  I think I agree with Fritz at this point.  Although Black has the nice pawn chain she also has doubled e-pawns.  Then again Black's Rf1 now has a half-open file.  Chess can be confusing at times.
10. Ne5 seemed like the only logical move.
The exchange of Ns was expected.
Development.  White's LSB is really chewing on serious granite.
13. e3 made more sense than to exchange B's and help Black develop her Queen.  Of course I'll be doubling my pawns.  Is a file considered half-open if only one play has two pawns on the file?
Attacking the backward pawn.
I was trying to develop a plan.  Positionally I had more space Q-side so I decided to push forward there.
No more DSBs.
At this point both GameKnot and fritz have the game as equal.
17. Bg4.  I have found that when I play stronger players it's a bad idea to leave pieces en prise as they tend to develop plans that result in my losing said piece.
GameKnot now gives a slight advantage (-0.21) to Black.
Continuing to gain space Q-side.
19. a3  I'm going slowly at this point as I'm not quite sure how to break through.  I know that I will not initiate the exchange of LSBs as I do not want e4 to be so reinforced.

22. Kg2 My thought was this was a nice waiting move plus it added protection to my pawns and allowed my Rs to move down to h1 g1 should that be necessary.

Both GameKnot and fritz were not happy with this move.  GameKnot recommended 22. Bxf5  exf5  23. Rfd1 Qf6  24. Ra3 Rh3  25. b5 Re8  26. Re3 Qh6  27. f3 Kf7  28. Qc2 Qh5  29. bxc6 bxc6  If I follow GN's recommendation the advantage to Black was -0.30.  As it was GN scored it -0.86.  

Fritz recommended 22. Bxf5 exf5 23. b5 Rc8 and then said that this would be equal.
attacking White's backward pawn.
GN has the advantage at -0.49 (for Black) while Fritz has the game equal.
White wins a pawn.
27...cxb5 28. axb5  Black now has a passed pawn to contend with.

28...a4 The saying "passed pawns must be pushed" comes to mind.  However according to GN Black went from -0.68 to -0.10 with that move.  I'm not quite sure why--should Black perhaps have moved 28...exf3  I'm not sure.  I do know that the next few moves wins a pawn back for White.
expected.
There's really no way to save e4 at this point.
We've moved into a double rook endgame.  GN now gives White the slight advantage +0.14
I mulled this move over for quite awhile
34. b6  All of these moves took a fair amount of time for me.  I did not want Black to move b6 as my analysis showed that would lose a pawn for White.

It was right about here that my opponent complimented my play thus far in the game.  It always nice when someone 300+ points better than you tells you that you are playing a good game.  She also told me that I had a draw on my hands if I played correctly.  I've never drawn against a 2000+ opponent so of course I felt the pressure.  I deliberated several days over the next sequence of moves.  I don't know if I would have worked so hard at it if my opponent had not told me that a draw was possible.  At any rate I worked out the correct moves but move 41 will undo it all.
I hoped Black might exchange Rs but she's too strong a player to do so.

Again my opponent complimented me.  GN has the score of the game as -0.01 and fritz has it equal.  While I don't know how equal the game is at this point while we're playing it I know that it's going well.  I guess I need to protect e5  [cue ominous music]

And this essentially loses the game for me.  Not my typical blunder where I give away a piece--just inexact play against a superior opponent and bad things happen.  My opponent let me know that Ra7! was the move I should have made.  

GN offered 41. Ra7  g6  42. Rxh7 Kxe5  43. Re7+ Kd5  44. Rd7+ Ke4  45. Re7+ Kd5
Fritz offered "41. Ra7!? should be examined more closely"  [sarcasm]You think so fritz?[end sarcasm]

I focused so much on keeping material even that I missed the threat caused by Ra7.  Ra7...Ra7...Ra7  Is see Ra7 in my nightmares.
GN now scores the game -1.05 and this number will now just increase.
This got a ? mark from fritz and GN didn't like it too much either.  I had a plan to attack belatedly g7 and h7 but it didn't work.
passed pawns must be pushed.
I figured I had to get to c3 and then worry about the other pawns.
I didn't want to allow connected passed pawns so I thought I'd just take out g7 first
For those keeping score at home GN has it at -3.02
I wondered if I kept giving check if I could somehow get a draw.  :tears:

And there is no way to stop at least one of Black's pawns from Queening.  I have to thank my opponent (thanks janet) for being so encouraging and helpful during the game.  She certainly did not have to take the time she did and it was much appreciated.

It seems that my positional game has improved (when I avoid stupid blunders) and my openings are good enough to get me into the middle game competitively.  What this game has clearly demonstrated to me is that it is time to dedicate the larger portion of my study time to endgames.

As always comments and input is appreciated.

I am not a fan of "rules" but black has started developing the first piece just now against 3 well placed pieces by white...
It is well known that dxc4 makes only an apparent waste of tempo for white.
This "squeezes" black's position a lot. But white hasn't got anything concretely yet.
A big mistake but black has almost no moves to play. Though he must have taken the knight and played Nh5 in order to release the position.

This was probably unwise but I wanted to take him out of his known system.

And white resigns with plenty of clock time left.  I spent a little time with the puzzle composer and it is difficult to see if Black is in a forced losing position.  By most standards even if White steps out of the attack the next 5-10 moves will not be fun for him.

This was great fun for me but must have been torture for my poor opponent.  Our grades were much closer at the start of the match so it's not a case of a simple crushing by a better player just a case of an unfortunate series of opening errors that were duly punished.
The Scandinavian or Centre-Counter is a tricky opening so both players have to be on the ball.
All standard stuff so far.
? but this is not recommended by the books.
Black goes chasing material at the cost of development.
? Another unnecessary Queen move when all his other pieces are still at home.
The Q is chased away the B protected and the g-file covered all in one move.
Once again the Q provides White with a tempo for development.
This at least prevents castling and again threatens to win material with ...Qxb2
Black is welcome to expend another tempo for the insignificant b-pawn.  White's minor pieces are gaining control of the board.
White completes his development and Black still only has his Queen out.  9 out of Black's first 10 moves have been Queen moves.

and then this non-Queen move is a pawn move that doesn't help develop any pieces.  In fact it deprives the Nb8 of its best square.  While this is a standard move in the Scandinavian it is usually several moves earlier as part of a plan to preserve the Q.  Now there were far more relevant moves to be made.
White takes aim at the centrally stranded King.
This saves the Q for the time being but deprives King Bishop and Knight of a useful square.
The N takes advantage of the pin on the pawn to attack the Q again.

?! or ?? depending on whether it was deliberate.  Black ignores the attack on the Q and belatedly starts to provide the space to develop his pieces.  Having invested so many tempi in the Q it seems strange to give it up now.  Perhaps it was just a blundering oversight.
White immediately heads for the holes at f6 and d6.
Black covers the holes by placing his N on a good square albeit this is a second move with the one remaining developed piece.
Now the second N reinforces the defence of f6.  It's a pity Black has lost his Q as his pawns look solid but draughty.  White can have a party on the black squares.
A mysterious little move.  I'm not sure now why I played it: probably to bolster the d-pawn so that the Q would not be tied to its defence after the inevitable ...Bg7
Now that Black has deprived his N of its best retreat square I push the pawn forward again to dislodge it.
Now White's path to victory is a smooth one.
This threatens mate in 1
This defends against that threat but not the next.  23.. Bxe6 would have been slightly better.
Tal sets the scene to his inferno with the Indian Defense opening which can easily morph into almost any defense of his choosing.
Bobotsov lays claim to the center as Tal preps his bishop's fianchetto along the h8-a1 diagonal.
Now that Tal's fiancetto is complete he can add the next ingredients that composes the alchemy of his inferno.
E77. King's Indian/ Six Pawn Attack.
E80. White plans to castle long and fight king-side but of course Tal knows that...
King-side development complete! Now into the inferno we shall delve!
White anticipates his O-O-O.
Tal continues with his plan to dominate the queenside by restricting White's ability to manuever with ease.
Tal subjects his queen to a discovered attack/sacrifice which proves to be his least necessary piece.
What's Tal's next move? Hmmm... 10...Nb6 seems sound attacking c4 with a fork on White's queen and bishop or perhaps 10...Re8 will suffice...
Tal chooses to continue mounting the pressure on White's queen-side while setting the stage for his Queen's dramatic suicide.
For white's next move 11. dxc5 dxc5 would've been abit more reasonable as to open the d-file and then 12. Nd5.
And now the moment we've all been awaiting!  Tal thrusts his queen into the pit of the inferno as the spectators gasp with awe! Now all Tal must do is stir the fire that it may burn ever fiercely!

White is now up in material but he must figure out how to use this to his advantage.  Meanwhile Tal eyeballs the b2 square and plans to open the diagonal for his bishop on g7 who's been waiting so patiently for its time to shine.
White moves his rook to safety and hopes to trade down material to ease the pressure and regain the initiative but as we shall see hope will soon be all White has left..
It is commonly agreed that 14. Qe1 would've been the better move here.  White does achieve the opening of the b-file but unfortunately (for him) it is to Tal's advantage.
Material is now even but Tal's position is clearly much better.
White activates his bishop and attacks c4.
With mounting pressure Tal ceases the b-file.

With White's d4 pawn free for the taking 16...Bxd4 would allow White to counter Tal's bishop with 17. Nb3 while safeguarding his vulnerable b2 square.  All would be well and return to normalcy.  But tsk tsk White's bishop is just abit too pesky...
Perhaps 17. Bxa6 would've been better gaining a pawn while trading down and activating his stagnant queen in the process...
With White's bishop safeguarding the b2 square Tal is free to lay claim to d4 opening the diagonal.  Tal keeps the fire raging and guns pointed at that b2 square.

Tal prevents a mounting attack on his valuable bishop with 19. Ne2 in which White would be more than happy to trade off.  Unfortunately (for white) 18...Bd7 19. Ne2...Na4 20. Nxd4...21. cxd4 is just a pipe dream!
Excuse me Sir Bishop... would you so kindly step away from the b-2 square so that I may more easily checkmate your king?
Thank you kindly...
21. Nxc3 Nc4 proves to be fatal for white ending with either a lost queen or mate.
Tal opens the 8th rank for his rook preparing to seize the c-file and maneuver his knight to a4.

Both b and c-files are possessed by Tal and his b2 pawn is once again invincable.  Trading
pieces doesn't seem to do much for White. At this point he doesn't seem to have very many options.
Once again Tal's bishop's diagonal is wide open.

he infernal blazes full throttle as White is left with few choices. Mate lingers in the air as the
tread (or perhaps noose?) White is hanging on gets tighter...
With both Tal's rooks charged on the c-file can you hear the bolt locking into place?
Oops... White just steps into a forced mate... See it?
Now it's mate in two....
Well I'm sure you see the mate by now if you hadn't already.  White decides to throw in the towel (or maybe take an ice cold bath.)
Offering the beloved king's gambit hoping that my opponent will accept it.

According to the opening books this seems to be quite a rare move to decline the gambit however one that I encounter quite often here on GameKnot especially when playing blitz games. The most common alternatives to 2... exf4 are the Falkbeer countergambit (2... d5) or the classical king's gambit declined (2... Bc5).

Playing just like the opponent would have taken the pawn. If he does now it transposes to the king's gambit accepted with the well-known Fischer defence (normal move-order: 1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 d6) so this is one more offer to accept the gambit.
Okay it seems my opponent doesn't like the KGA.

Doesn't really do anything good besides pinning the knight which won't hurt my opponent. Being greedy I guess the idea behind this move was winning the pawn e5 (idea: 4... some dummy move like h6 5. fxe5 dxe5 6. Nxe5). However d4 or Nc3 would have been much better.
Attacking e4...

... so I have to defend it. fxe4 would also have been an attractive option which may continues: 5... dxe5 6. Nxe5 Qd4 7. Nxc6 Qxe4+ 8. Qe2 Qxe2+ 9. Kxe2 a6 10. Ba4 Bd7 with a small advantage for White.
Prepares castling king's side.
Probably not a bad move but this time I *really* could have taken the pawn to gain advantage: 6. fxe5 dxe5 7. Nxe5 and the pawn is won this time.
Time to open the center!
Instead of freeing up the d-File Fritz suggests 7... Ng4.
? I could have won a pawn with 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. fxe5 Ng4 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. h3 Nh6 etc.
? Overlooking the fork on f2.
The only sane choice.

And now I resigned assuming that my queen is lost. I thought taking back with the rook is no option as Black would take my queen on d1 then - not noticing that it is defended by my knight on c3! So I should have kept on playing! After 11. Rxf2 Bxf2 (Qxd1? 12. Nxd1 Bxf2 13. Nxf2 and White is up in material) black is better - Fritz rates the position as -0.91 - but it isn't completely lost so far for White. Conclusion: I shouldn't react that impulsively to opponent's moves no single game has ever been won by resigning.

Played after the first long think of the game.  I guessed he was trying to weigh up whether to play the 4 Pawns the Saemisch or the Main Line.  This flexible move allows variations of all three though it doesn't particularly help the Saemisch as it deprives the Ng1 of e2.
Again White refrains from Nf3 causing me to think awhile.  Eventually I reasoned that if 6...e5 would have been my move with the N on f3 it must still be good with it on g1 ...
White plays the knee-jerk response.  Both his bishops have good ranges albeit largely contested by Black's pieces and pawns.

?! I want to bring my QN to c5 to attack e4 and generally cause a nuisance not such a good plan if White is really planning to play f3 and the Saemisch.  This early thrust inhibits White from playing a version of the Bayonet Attack with 8. b4 thus protecting c5 from disturbance.  Sometimes this is only played after the N has gone to c5 but that seems to be locking the stable door after the horse has bolted.  In retrospect I think I would have been better preparing immediately for kingside action with 7...Ne8.

!? Unexpected - but maybe it shouldn't have been.  White beats Black to the first aggressive gesture on the kingside and this sets the tone of the game.  Black never gets to play a typical King's Indian strategy.
Ghastly memories of the thrashing I received at the hands of Martin's teammate Paul Paxton-Doggett earlier in the season informed this move designed to stop the pawn in its tracks.
A dual purpose move allowing Qd2 by preventing the annoying ...Ng4 and also supporting the potential pawn advance g4.
This develops the N without blocking in the Bc8 and heads as planned for c5 whence it is ready for action on either wing theoretically.
White also develops his N to the wing clearly prepared to give up the chance of castling kingside.
This bishop often impales itself for nothing more than a pawn on h3 so why not swap it there for White's N?  Blacks lsb is often a liability in the King's Indian anyway.

The idea behind this move was to inhibit White's planned g-pawn advance since on g4 it would be pinned against the Rh3.  I hoped thereby to slow down White's attack sufficiently to generate some activity for myself.  This move also connects my Rooks.
White prepares the typical Bh6 thrust and queenside castling.

This move was played to prevent 13. Bh6.  It also gives Black's N another retreat square so that Black can possibly advance his f-pawn - but actually I was already feeling that it was too late to play such a move because White was already ready to play g4.  If Black played ...Ng8 followed by ...f5 he would merely be weakening his own kingside with little prospect of getting an attack going.

Played so that if White swapped B for N on c5 Black wouldn't have to recapture with the d-pawn thus giving White's advanced d-pawn scope for a future advance.  I think this was too slow though.  An immediate 13...Nc5 followed by ...a4 might have given Black the start of an attack which at least would have given White cause to think about something other than his kingside attack.  White's B is much more concerned with the holes in Black's kingside anyway.
!  I'd expected Rh1 to defend the Rh3 preparing g2-g4-g5; but this prepares doubling on the g-file: much more powerful.
Black finally gets his N where he wants it but it's a useless spectator for most of the game.
White over-defends e4 and covers the squares b3 and a4 while setting up a piercing glare at Black's king.  It should only take a few well-aimed blows for his majesty to be fatally exposed.
Played to prevent 16. f4 when neither ...exf4 allowing 17. e5 nor any other move allowing 17. f5 or 17. fxe5 looked attractive.
I didn't think I could allow 18. g5+ when my Queen's discovered attack on the Rh3 would have been useless though it would of course still have discouraged 19. gxf6.
Now the g-pawn is free to move and g6 and g7 are looking very weak.

I'd been hoping for this since it seems to reduce White's attacking options but it pushes Black further back into his shell.  I was now 100% preoccupied with defence abandoning any ideas of counter-attacking on the queenside with for example ...a4 followed by ...Nb3+ (a possibility I've only just seen) ...axb3 and ...Ra1+.  Whether Black could achieve such a sequence and whether it would have been worth trying I leave to the reader to consider ...
Black couldn't hold on to the extra pawn so didn't try to.
Contrast White's broad acres of country estate with Black's cramped city tenement apartment!
Now f7 is double-attacked.
Surely to be followed by tripling on the f-file...
I thought: I'm ready for you here!
Still I hold!
!  Black can risk ...Nxf6 if he likes but gxf6 delivers a horrible fork.
?? This throws it away but Martin pointed out that 29. Be6 was on its way anyway so Black was already doomed.
The N is pinned against the undefended Q.
A few defiant gestures from the wriggling corpse-to-be...

and two pieces down without a hope of redemption I resigned.  If you're going to play the King's Indian you really have to get your attack in quickly.  I dillied and I dallied and I couldn't find my way home.
One of my favorite openings because it throws the other player on their own resources.
So far sticking to what little "book" there is.
This move makes my position a little safer as with the Knight on Black's KB3 it eliminates the possiblity of ...Q-R5 ch in the future.
We're now out of the books. I'm now going to look for a chance to seize the center with my as-yet-held-back center Pawns.
Now my QB is free to develop.
With the position already looking like an endgame my King should be perfectly safe in the center. Now I just need to develop my KN and place my Rooks.
Black still needs to castle but it appears an even middle game has been reached.
I would have preferred to play QR-QB1 but Black is assaulting my QRP at the moment.
If I can exchange my Knight for my opponent's Bishop I'll have an endgame advantage. With the Pawn position fluid the long-range B is superior.
Oops! Black forgot about my B hiding at KN2.
Now I have a significant material advantage. Strategy is trade down and avoid complications. if I can get the Queens off the board my life would be good.
Getting an exchange of minor pieces in is a good start.
I double on the file.
Another blunder. Black didn't count the number of attacking pieces. I can now win a Rook.
The rest should be easy.
I plan to trade a Rook for a Knight and Pawn removing Black's last piece and setting up a flank majority that should soon generate a new Queen.
Done.
And Black resigns as the Pawn cannot be stopped.

Ideally I like taking control of the center by advancing my center pawns.  I think that it gives a kind of spatial advantage.
Black attacks my d-pawn so I defend.  I usually do not like moving my c-pawn to c3 because it blocks my knights optimal square but I liked strengthening my pawn structure.
He attacks the pawn so I pin his knight to his king.
He attacks my bishop so I retreat a little but I keep the knight pinned to the king.

He defends his king and removes the pin off of his king. I think that Knight to f3 is a really good move because it develops a new piece adds a defender to my d-pawn and I am preparing to castle king side.
We exchange pawns he checks my king and I defend with my knight. So far I like my position.
We both castle king side.  I pull back my bishop to c2 because I feel like I will be able to have a great attack on his king side with my two bishops and my queen.

At this point I think I have a really good advantage and I believed that the end was going to be near. I had a general Idea of how I was going to attack so I threatened mate with Qd2 and he guards by moving his knight to f5.

I attack his knight with my pawn and he takes my pawn at d4. I felt like he was trying to go 13...Ncxd4 14. Nfxd4 Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Nfxd4 but now that I look back at this position it might have been okay to take his night on d4 because my bishop is guarding my queen so it could have been. 13... Ncxd4 14. Nfxd4 Qxd4 15. gxf5 Qxd3 16. Bxd3 this would have been fine but i did not see this at the time so I took his night on f5 with my pawn.
After he took my night with his bishop I pushed my furthest f pawn to f6.  I threatened mate again. I knew that he was either going to take my bishop or push his g pawn up.
he took my bishop to stop the threat of mate and I took his pawn and attacked his rook. I had a plan that I thought was full proof.

At this point I thought that I had the game won. I thought that I had seen every move that he could make and I thought it was over. No matter what he moved I could easily see a forced mate if he moves his king anywhere I have forced mate and I thought that no matter what piece he moved he couldn't stop the attack but I was so into the game that I had missed a simple move.
Rh8 and that guards the pawn so I can't checkmate. I was pretty shocked that I had missed that simple move after this point the game started to get a little dangerous for me.

I simply take back material but I do not like my situation here first of all my king isn't very protected my knight is probably going to be driven back by his pawns and their is a discovered attack on my queen that can be used.
Yup he takes my pawn opening having the rook attack my queen so I move it out of the way and attack his bishop.
I think that this move was a blunder on for black because it gave me a nice forking opportunity. black should have just guarded his bishop with his f-pawn that would have also driven my knight back.
I fork his his bishop and Queen so he takes my pawn and checks my king with his bishop.
I take his bishop with my king and then he wants to trade Queens which is fine by me but first I want to improve my position just a little bit so...
I go Rg1+ putting my rook on the open file and he moves his king away
I felt really pressured in my situation so I was happy to exchange queens to relieve the pressure I think he was to.
I wanted to develop my bishop so I could use my Queen rook so I checked his king with it.

I was really worried about my position and it took me along time to figure out what my next move would be. Finally the only sensible move that I saw was Ne5 getting my knight to safety and attacking his bishop.
This was the move that i was hoping he would not make the only thing I could do was take his bishop and if he took back with his king I would have a checking opportunity.

When we got to this position my position not very good if I do not do something fast black is going to take up all my pawns with his rook. It took me about 10 minutes to find the only move that could save me for now.
I was really happy with this move not only did this protect both of my pawns but I was also offering a trade of rooks which I really wanted the trade.

He brings his rook to g6 and I decide to make the rook trade I just really wanted to simplify the situation as much as I could but I new that I was in trouble because right now I think his position is better than mine.  His pawns are in a better position than mine and I can tell that once the pawns start to come down it is going to be tough for me to keep him from queening.  I figure that if I can somehow get my king to e5 that I can somehow hold the position.

I was lucky that black did not really have a good way of preventing my king from getting to e5. Now that I look back at this position I realize that I like my position because all of my pieces were protected but at the time I thought that I was barely holding on.  I didn't think that I was losing but I didn't feel like I was winning.
A strange opening but it seems to work.
A mistake; there is no retreat for the white queen.
Definitely should have played Nxd4 instead. (Queen trap!)
Stephen now noticing that his queen is in peril urges his team to give her an escape square.
A blunder? I think yes.
The queen gets pushed around while my rook develops.
Right now my pieces slowly creep over to attack the white king.
If I took the f3 knight right away then if gxf3 my knight could no longer come to e4.
A bold move; I did not even realize this threat. But I have something better...
I told my team: Although this move is risky--and I showed them the variations--often times you have to be risky in chess. I believe we made the best decision.
This is Stephen's team's best move since Qxb1 is met with Qxa5+ Kd1 Nc3+ forking the king and queen; Bxd8 is met with Bb4+ Nd2(forced) Bxd2#
A blunder indeed. All it did was waste a move and make way for mate. Probably best for white is Rb2.
Stephen later asked: "What if I didn't take the bishop?" Answer: Mate would still be forced (Qd2#) or if b4 then King move and mate on the next turn (Qc2# or Bd2#).
